  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:11-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " describe the part which the priests and Levitical singers and musicians took in the solemn act of transferring the ark to the temple-a matter entirely passed over in the narrative in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which confines itself to the main transaction. The mention of the priests gives occasion for the remark, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"for all the priests present had sanctified themselves, but the courses were not to be observed,\" i.e., the courses of the priests (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") could not be observed. The festival was so great, that not merely the course appointed to perform the service of that week, but also all the courses had sanctified themselves and co-operated in the celebration. In reference to the construction לשׁמור אין, cf. Ew. 321, b.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
